      <div class="content">
                
        <br><br><br><br><br><br>
        Now, let’s make it functional.<br><br>

        With <b>light</b>, the material casts soft shadows. Its texture stands out on its own.With <b>soil</b>, it biodegrades even faster.<br><h1>plant pot</h1> can be the perfect fit.
        <h2>*Or if you have a better idea - like a lampshade or a sun-catcher - bring it to life.</h2><br>

        Now it’s your turn to <b>design your own plant pot.</b><br> Use any object you have as a mould, and feel free to adjust the recipe to explore new textures, forms, and properties.
       
        Over time, it will naturally break down - cracking, splitting, slowly fading. Then, <b>enjoy its trace of time</b> and let these marks of change tell their story.
        And when that time comes, you can <b>repair it by adding more paste.</b>

        <br><br>Let it grow, adapt, and return to the earth - just as it began.<br><br>
        
        
        
        <h1>Tips.</h1>

        <b>To shape it..</b><br>
        <span class="spacing"><b>- </b>Use a tray, mould, or any oven-safe kitchen tools.</span><br>
        <div class="slideshow1">
          <div class="slide">
            <img src="a-1-1.jpg">
